{{Quote|The way Malani stares at me with those big, moony eyes... Reminds me of the way Latara stares at Teebo.|[[Wicket Wystri Warrick/Legends|Wicket W. Warrick]]|<ref name="1-03">{{Ewoks|Rampage of the Phlogs}}</ref>}}
'''Malani''' was a [[Gender/Legends|female]] [[Ewok/Legends|Ewok]] from the forest moon of [[Endor/Legends|Endor]]. She was the daughter of [[Warok/Legends|Warok]] and [[Batcheela (Ewok)|Batcheela]] and the younger sister of [[Teebo/Legends|Teebo]].

==Biography==
When she was just a [[Wokling/Legends|wokling]], Malani and the rest of the children of [[Bright Tree Village/Legends|Bright Tree Village]] were kidnapped by a band of [[Dulok/Legends|Duloks]] led by King [[Vulgarr/Legends|Vulgarr]], who wanted to make a meal of them. Through the efforts of her father, brother, and other warriors from the village, Malani and the woklings were saved.<ref name="The Adventures of Teebo: A Tale of Magic and Suspense">''[[The Adventures of Teebo: A Tale of Magic and Suspense]]''</ref> Later, she helped [[Princess/Legends|Princess]] [[Kneesaa a Jari Kintaka/Legends|Kneesaa a Jari Kintaka]], the boys and the female villagers to protect the village against Captain [[Krag (Zorbian)|Krag]] and his [[Zorbian space pirates|gang's]] attack.<ref name="rites">[[Ewoks (1985) 2|''Ewoks'' (1985) 2]]</ref>

[[File:Malani.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Malani as a wokling]]
As she got older, Malani received a somewhat oversized hood at the [[Festival of Hoods]] as part of her status, but insisted on keeping it.<ref name="1-01">{{Ewoks|The Cries of the Trees}}</ref> She also developed a crush on [[Wicket Wystri Warrick/Legends|Wicket W. Warrick]].<ref name="1-03" /><ref name="1-10">{{Ewoks|Wicket's Wagon}}</ref><ref name="2-21">{{Ewoks|Malani the Warrior}}</ref> Nevertheless, she was often cast out by the adolescent [[Ewok/Legends|Ewoks]] in her brother's circle of friends and forced to play with the very young Ewoks, which she did not enjoy, as they were too young for her.<ref name="TV" />

She once ran away after she overheard Wicket insulting her. Wicket went after her and brought her back to the village, apologizing for hurting her feelings.<ref name="1-03" /> Their friendship improved enough for them to work together both rebuilding Wicket's [[Erpham Warrick|grandfather's]] [[Ewok battle wagon|battle wagon]] and destroying it to stop the [[Dulok/Legends|Duloks]] who stole it.<ref name="1-10" /> Malani would later be a victim during the [[stranglethorn crisis]], later saved by Kneesaa, Wicket and the [[Trome]]s.<ref name="1-11">{{Ewoks|The Three Lessons}}</ref> She was also among the woklings who went with Wicket and his friends into [[Horville's Hut of Horrors]].<ref name="2-16">{{Ewoks|Horville's Hut of Horrors (episode)}}</ref> Wicket would finally learn of Malani's feelings for him sometime later, when he was interested in another girl, [[Chirita]].<ref name="2-21" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Had we done a third season, I'm sure we would have done a few more stories about Malani, who was always a favorite character.|''Ewoks'' associate producer and story editor Paul Dini in 1988|<ref name="Starlog Yearbook 3">{{Starlog|Yearbook Vol. 3|Saturday Morning "Star Wars"}}</ref>}}
In the [[Ewoks: Season One|first season]] of [[Ewoks (television series)|''Ewoks'']], Malani was voiced by [[Alyson Court]] and during the [[Ewoks: Season Two|second season]] by [[Jeanne Reynolds]].<ref name="Starlog Yearbook 3" />

Malani was one of six 8-inch plush woklings made by [[Kenner Products|Kenner]] based upon the six woklings seen in [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']]. While the character names of Malani, [[Nippet/Legends|Nippet]], and [[Wiley (Ewok)|Wiley]] were established prior in the ''Star Wars: Ewoks'' television series, the other three&mdash;[[Mookiee]], [[Leeni]], and [[Gwig]]&mdash;have yet to be attributed to their respective characters seen in ''Return of the Jedi''.

